Diagnosis. All specimens collected from China bear the following characters: the male malar area nearly as long as the width of mandible base (
Fig. 3
), metafemur, metatibia strongly swollen, and metatrochanter ventrally with angular projection (
Fig. 6
), basal margin of S 5 with two transverse rows of spines numbered in 3 respectively at both sides (
Fig. 5
); the female malar area about one-third as long as the width of mandible base (
Fig. 13
), second marginal crossvein angulated medially (
Fig. 14
), metasomal terga with short, simple, laterally-directed hairs on posterior marginal zones, T 2 with broad orange apical margin (
Fig. 15
). All these characters diagnosed our specimens as
T . ( T .) sladeni
Cockerell, 1913
.

Distribution. China (Yunnan), India (Assam, Khasia Hills;
Cockerell, 1913
).
